<P1>5. The Appellant filed a Notice of Objection to the Reassessments on May 17, 2016.</P1>
<P1>6. In response to the Notice of Objection, the Minister confirmed the Reassessments. The Notice of Confirmation was dated December 12, 2017.</P1>
<P1>7. The Appellant filed a Notice of Appeal on February 16, 2018.</P1></P>
<BLOCK3><TI>ASSUMPTIONS</TI>
<P><P1>8. In determining the Appellant's tax liabilities for the 2012 and 2013 taxation years, the Minister assumed the following facts:
<P2>a. the facts stated and admitted above;</P2>
<P2>b. Queenslake Pharmacy is a taxable Canadian corporation which carries on a pharmacy business;</P2>
<P2>c. the Appellant and Younan Mikhail (&ldquo;Younan&rdquo;) are the shareholders of the Queenslake Pharmacy (the &ldquo;Shareholders&rdquo;);</P2>
<P2>d. the Appellant is married to Younan;</P2>
<P2>e. Younan owns 51% of the shares of the Queenslake Pharmacy;</P2>
<P2>f. the Appellant owns 49% of the shares of the Queenslake Pharmacy;</P2>
<P2>g. the Queenslake Pharmacy purchased pharmaceutical products from different drug manufacturers and suppliers including Mylan and Actavis (the &ldquo;Pharmaceutical Manufacturers&rdquo;);</P2>
<P2>h. the Pharmaceutical Manufacturers offered rebates and incentives to the Queenslake Pharmacy dependent on the volume of the Queenslake Pharmacy's purchases from the Pharmaceutical Manufacturers (the &ldquo;Rebates&rdquo;).</P2>
<P2>i. there were discussions between the Pharmaceutical Manufacturers and the Queenslake Pharmacy regarding the purpose and amounts of the Rebates;</P2>
<P2>j. the Appellant and Younan as representatives of Queenslake Pharmacy had a choice to receive Rebates from the Pharmaceutical Manufacturers in the form of cheques, gift cards. AMEX Traveller's Cheques, team points (redeemable for merchandise) and/or pre-loaded credit cards;</P2>
<P2>k. the Appellant and Younan as representatives of Queenslake Pharmacy received Rebates from the Pharmaceutical Manufacturers which include but not limited to traveller's cheques, reloadable credit cards and gift basket.</P2>
<P2>l. the Rebates would not have been paid if it were not for the business relations hips between the Queenslake Pharmacy and the Pharmaceutical Manufacturers;</P2>
<P2>m. the Rebates were based on pre-defined percentages determined in advance of purchases by the Queenslake Pharmacy from the Pharmaceutical Manufacturers;</P2>
<P2>n. the Rebates would not have occurred if the Queenslake Pharmacy were not buying and selling the Pharmaceutical Manufacturers' products (the &ldquo;Products&rdquo;)</P2>
<P2>o. the Queenslake Pharmacy, through its Shareholders, was aware of the Rebates;</P2>
<P2>p. the Queenslake Pharmacy, through the Shareholders, was involved in choosing the payment method of the Rebates;</P2>
<P2>q. the Rebates, as set out in the following chart, were received by the Queenslake Pharmacy or its Shareholders, but were not reported in the Queenslake Pharmacy's income:
