<P2>r. the Shareholders appropriated the Rebates referred to in the previous subparagraph as follows (the &ldquo;Appropriated Rebates&rdquo;):
<P3>i. Younan appropriated $9,812 and $1,882 of the Rebates in the 2010 and 2011 calendar years, respectively; and</P3>
<P3>ii. Helen appropriated $9,952 and $2,525 of the Rebates in the 2012 and 2013 calendar years, respectively.</P3></P2>
<P2>s. No employees of Queenslake Pharmacy other than the Appellant and Younan received a benefit in the form of the Appropriated Rebates.</P2></P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>C.</N><TI>ISSUES TO BE DECIDED</TI>
<P><P1>9. Whether the Minister properly included Unreported Rebates and Incentives of $9,952 and $2,525 in the 2012 and 2013 taxation years, respectively.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>D.</N><TI>STATUTORY PROVISIONS, GROUNDS RELIED ON AND RELIEF SOUGHT</TI>
<P><P1>10. The Attorney General relies on subsections 3, 15(1), 152(9), and 246(1) of the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM>, R.S.C. 1985. c.1 (5th Supp.) as amended (&ldquo;<EM>Ac</EM>&rdquo;).</P1>
<P1>11. Whereas Queenslake Pharmacy failed to report all of the Rebates it earned in the course of doing business with the Pharmaceutical Manufacturers, and whereas some of those Rebates were appropriated by the Appellant in her capacity as a shareholder, therefore the Minister has properly reassessed the Appellant to include the Appropriated Rebates as the Appellant's income for the 2012 and 2013 taxation years pursuant to subsection 15(1) of the <EM>Act</EM>.</P1>
<P1>12. In the alternative, Queenslake Pharmacy conferred a benefit on the Appellant in the form of the Appropriated Rebates. The Rebates are therefore part of her income by operation of subsection 246(1) of the <EM>Act</EM>.</P1>
<P1>13. The Attorney General requests that the appeal be dismissed.</P1></P>
<P>All of which is respectfully submitted.</P>
