<BLOCK1><TI><UNDER>NOTICE OF APPEAL</UNDER></TI>
<P>TAKE NOTICE THAT, <EM>Younan Mikhail SIN</EM>[#omitted]appeals to the Court from assessment of taxation years 2010 and 2011. Notice of Confirmation for which was dated Jan 25, 2018. See attached.
<P1>A. Reasons for the appeal.&mdash;The company was assessed for incentives received in the above years that were not declared as income. In addition however the employees that received the incentives were also assessed for the same amounts resulting in double taxation. When CRA brought it to our attention that the incentives might be not have been reported properly, it offered an opportunity to correct our tax returns without penalties, only arrears interest will apply. Double taxation in a punitive measure.
<P2>In addition on further review with the employee, the amounts indicated are not correct. In particular the payments of $6,078.01 and $3,734,64 in 2010 were not received. The amount received was $1136.71 only in 2011. See attached.</P2></P1>
<P1>B. Statement of relevant facts in support of the appeal.&mdash;In the case of <CASEREF><SOC>Chopp v. The Queen</SOC></CASEREF>, Mojan J. stated the following: If a shareholder is also an employee of the corporation and receives a benefit in his capacity as employee, the value of that benefit would be tasted under paragraph 6(1)(a) of the act. A corporation is ordinarily permitted to deduct as a business expense the cost of a benefit received or enjoyed by an employee. A corporation, however, is not permitted to deduct any amount with respect to a benefit conferred on a shareholder qua shareholder because the corporate/shareholder relationship is not incidental to the corporation's business.
<P2>Both individuals (Younan and Hellen Mikhail SIN[#omitted]) that received incentives were employees of the company.</P2></P1></P>
<P>I ELECT to have the informal procedure provided by sections 18.1 to 18.28 of the <EM>Tax Court of Canada Act</EM> apply to this appeal.</P>
