<P2>r. the Shareholders appropriated the Rebates referred to in the previous subparagraph as follows (the &ldquo;Appropriated Rebates&rdquo;):
<P3>i. Younan appropriated $9,812 and $1,882 of the Rebates in the 2010 and 2011 calendar years, respectively;</P3>
<P3>ii. Helen appropriated $9,952 and $2,525 of the Rebates in the 2012 and 2013 calendar years, respectively;</P3></P2>
<P2>s. No employees of Queenslake Pharmacy other than the Appellant and Hellen received a benefit in the form of the Appropriated Rebates.</P2>
<P2>t. In determining that the Appellant made a misrepresentation attributable to neglect, carelessness, or wilful default, in filing his income tax returns for the 2010 and 2011 taxation years, the Minister relied on the facts set out in the previous paragraphs, together with the following facts:
<P3>i. Queenslake Pharmacy reported as income all Rebates paid by cheques issued to the Appellant;</P3>
<P3>iii. a material portion of the Rebates were selected to be paid by methods other than a cheque;</P3>
<P3>iv. the Rebates not paid by cheque were not reported as income by the Queenslake Pharmacy;</P3>
<P3>v. the Appellant is aware of the Rebates;</P3>
<P3>vi. the Appellant was involved in choosing the method of payment of the Rebates;</P3>
<P3>vii. the Appropriated Rebates were used for the Shareholders' personal use;</P3>
<P3>viii. there is no relationship between the Shareholders and the Pharmaceutical Manufacturers outside of the business relationship surrounding the Appellant;</P3>
<P3>ix. rebates in the pharmaceutical industry are very common and have consistently been treated as taxable income;</P3>
<P3>x. the Shareholders began the pharmacy business in 2002 and were well aware of the appropriate treatment of the Rebates;</P3>
<P3>xi. the Shareholders did not keep proper records of the Rebates received;</P3>
<P3>xii. the Shareholders did not include these benefits in the calculation of their personal income reported for tax; and</P3>
<P3>xiii. the amount of Rebates which the Appellant failed to report were substantial compared to the total amount of income he reported in the 2010 and 2011 taxation years.</P3></P2></P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>C.</N><TI>ISSUES TO BE DECIDED</TI>
<P><P1>9. The issues to be decided are whether:
<P2>a. the Minister was entitled to reassess the Appellant's income tax returns for the 2010 and 2011 taxation years beyond the normal reassessment period; and</P2>
<P2>b. the Minister properly included Unreported Rebates and Incentives of $9.812 and $1,882 in the 2010 and 2011 taxation years, respectively.</P2></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>D.</N><TI>STATUTORY PROVISIONS, GROUNDS RELIED ON AND RELIEF SOUGHT</TI>
<P><P1>10. The Attorney General relies on sections subsections 3, 15(1), 152(4), 152(9) and 246(1) of the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM>, R.S.C. 1985. c.1 (5th Supp.) as amended (&ldquo;<EM>Act</EM>&rdquo;).</P1>
<P1>11. Whereas Queenslake Pharmacy failed to report all of the Rebates it earned in the course of doing business with the Pharmaceutical Manufacturers, and whereas some of those Rebates were appropriated by the Appellant in his capacity as a shareholder, therefore the Minister has properly reassessed the Appellant to include the Appropriated Rebates as the Appellant's income for the 2010 and 2011 taxation years pursuant to subsection 15(1) of the <EM>Act</EM>.</P1>
<P1>12. In the alternative, Queenslake Pharmacy conferred a benefit on the Appellant in the form of the Appropriated Rebates. The Rebates are therefore part of his income by operation of subsection 246(1) of the <EM>Act</EM>.</P1>
<P1>13. Subsection 152(4) of the Act authorizes reassessment at any time where a taxpayer has made any misrepresentation attributable to neglect, carelessness or wilful default. The Appellant made such misrepresentation, therefore the Minister was not out of time to reassess his 2010 and 2011 taxation years.</P1>
<P1>14. The Attorney General requests that the appeal be dismissed.</P1></P>
<P>All of which is respectfully submitted.</P>
