<BLOCK0><TI>SCHEDULE 4 (<EM>Section 4</EM>) NOTICE OF APPEAL (INFORMAL PROCEDURE)</TI>
<BLOCK1><TI><UNDER>NOTICE OF APPEAL</UNDER></TI>
<P>TAKE NOTICE THAT <EM>1526818 Ontario Inc BN: 8539874444RC0001</EM> appeals to the Court from assessments of taxation years ending October 31, 2010 to 2013. Notice of Confirmation for which was dated Nov 6, 2017. See attached letter re Application for Extension of time to file a Notice of Appeal.
<P1>A. Reasons for the appeal.&mdash;The company was assessed for incentives received in the above years that were not declared as income. In addition however the employees that received the incentives were also assessed for the same amounts resulting in double taxation. When CRA brought it to our attention that the incentives might be not have been reported properly, it offered an opportunity to correct our tax returns without penalties, only arrears interest will apply. Double taxation in a punitive measure.
<P2>In addition on further review with the employees, the amounts indicated are not correct. In particular the payments of $6,078.01 and $3,734.64 in 2010 were not received. The amount received was $1136.71 only in 2011. They only remember receiving amounts under $1,000. The amount received in 2012 was $6,415 and in 2013 $3,737.93. See attached.</P2></P1>
<P1>B. Statement of relevant facts in support of the appeal.&mdash;In the case of <CASEREF><SOC>Chopp v. The Queen</SOC></CASEREF>, Mojan J. stated the following: If a shareholder is also an employee of the corporation and receives a benefit in his capacity as employee, the value of that benefit would be taxed under paragraph 6(1)(a) of the act. A corporation is ordinarily permitted to deduct as a business expense the cost of a benefit received or enjoyed by an employee. A corporation, however, is not permitted to deduct any amount with respect to a benefit conferred on a shareholder qua shareholder because the corporate/shareholder relationship is not incidental to the corporation's business.
<P2>Both individuals (Younan Mikhail SIN [#omitted]and Hellen Mikhail SIN [#omitted]that received incentives were employees of the company.</P2></P1></P>
<P>I ELECT to have the informal procedure provided by sections 18.1 to 18.28 of the <EM>Tax Court of Canada Act</EM> apply to this appeal.</P>
