<BLOCK1><TI>REPLY TO THE NOTICE OF APPEAL</TI>
<P>In reply to the Notice of Appeal with respect to the taxation years end ed October 31, 2010, October 31, 2011, October 31, 2012 and October 31, 2013, the Attorney General of Canada (the &ldquo;Attorney General&rdquo;) says:</P>
<BLOCK2><N>A.</N><TI>PRELIMINARY OBJECTION</TI>
<P><P1>By way of preliminary objection, the Attorney General states that the Appeals for the taxation year ended October 31, 2013 ought to be quashed on the basis that the Minister of National Revenue (the &ldquo;Minister&rdquo;) has reassessed nil tax, interest and penalties.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>B.</N><TI>STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<P><P1>1. With respect to the facts alleged in the Notice of Appeal, the Attorney General:
<P2>a. states that except as expressly admitted herein, the Attorney General does not admit any allegation of fact contained in the Notice of Appeal;</P2>
<P2>b. admits the Appellant was reassessed to include unreported rebates and incentives in the taxation years ended October 31, 2010, October 31, 2011, October 31, 2012 and October 31, 2013;</P2>
<P2>c. states that the Appellant's unreported rebates and incentives for the taxation years ended October 31, 2010, October 31, 2011, October 31, 2012 and October 31, 2013 were $6,078, $4,871, $8,744 and $4,480, respectively;</P2>
<P2>d. admits that Younan Mikhail and Helen Mikhail appropriated the rebates and incentives referred in paragraph 1.c. above;</P2>
<P2>e. admits the authenticity of the following documents and states that the documents speak for themselves:
<P3>i. the letter from the Canada Revenue Agency (&ldquo;CRA&rdquo;) to Angelo Carere dated November 6, 2017; and</P3>
<P3>ii. the Notice of Confirmation from the CRA to the Appellant dated November 6, 2017.</P3></P2>
<P2>f. states that the chart dated March 19, 2018 attached to the Notice of Appeal was submitted by way of evidence and improperly attached;</P2>
<P2>g. states that the remainder of the Notice of Appeal constitutes argument or advances the relief sought, and denies any facts incidentally alleged and holds the Appellant to the strict proof thereof.</P2></P1></P></BLOCK2>
