<BLOCK3><TI>ASSUMPTIONS</TI>
<P><P1>13. In determining the Appellant's tax liabilities for the taxation years ended October 31, 2010, October 31, 2011, October 31, 2012 and October 31, 2013, the Minister assumed the following facts:
<P2>a. the facts stated and admitted above;</P2>
<P2>b. the Appellant is a taxable Canadian corporation which carries on a pharmacy business;</P2>
<P2>c. Younan Mikhail (&ldquo;Younan&rdquo;) and Helen Mikhail (&ldquo;Helen&rdquo;) are the shareholders of the Appellant (the &ldquo;Shareholders&rdquo;);</P2>
<P2>d. Younan is married to Helen;</P2>
<P2>e. the Appellant has a fiscal year end of October 31;</P2>
<P2>f. Younan owns 51% of the shares of the Appellant;</P2>
<P2>g. Helen owns 49% of the shares of the Appellant;</P2>
<P2>h. the Appellant purchased pharmaceutical products from different drug manufacturers and suppliers including Mylan and Actavis (the &ldquo;Pharmaceutical Manufacturers&rdquo;);</P2>
<P2>i. the Pharmaceutical Manufacturers offered rebates and incentives to the Appellant dependent on the volume of the Appellant's purchases from the Pharmaceutical Manufacturers (the &ldquo;Rebates&rdquo;);</P2>
<P2>j. there were discussions between the Pharmaceutical Manufacturers and the Appellant regarding the purpose and amounts of the Rebates;</P2>
<P2>k. the Appellant had a choice to receive Rebates from the Pharmaceutical Manufacturers in the form of cheques, gift cards, AMEX Traveller's Cheques, team points (redeemable for merchandise) and/or pre-loaded credit cards;</P2>
<P2>l. the Appellant or its Shareholders received Rebates from the Pharmaceutical Manufacturers which include but not limited to traveller's cheques, reloadable credit cards and gift basket.</P2>
<P2>m. the Rebates would not have been paid if it were not for the business relationships between the Appellant and the Pharmaceutical Manufacturers;</P2>
<P2>n. the Rebates were earned by the Appellant and not by the Shareholders;</P2>
<P2>o. the Rebates were based on pre-defined percentages determined in advance of purchases by the Appellant from the Pharmaceutical Manufacturers;</P2>
<P2>p. the Rebates would not have occurred if the Appellant were not buying and selling the Pharmaceutical Manufacturers' products (the &ldquo;Products&rdquo;);</P2>
<P2>q. the Appellant, through the Shareholders, was aware of the Rebates;</P2>
<P2>r. the Appellant, through the Shareholders, was involved in choosing the payment method of the Rebates;</P2>
<P2>s. the Rebates, as set out in the following chart, were received by the Appellant or its Shareholders, but were not reported in the Appellant's income:
