<P2>t. the Shareholders appropriated the Rebates referred to in the previous subparagraph as follows (the &ldquo;Appropriated Rebates&rdquo;):
<P3>i. Younan appropriated $9,812 and $1,882 of the Rebates in the 2010 and 2011 calendar years, respectively;</P3>
<P3>ii. Helen appropriated $9,952 and $2,525 of the Rebates in the 2012 and 2013 calendar years, respectively;</P3></P2>
<P2>u. In determining that the Appellant made a misrepresentation attributable to neglect, carelessness, or wilful default, in filing its income tax returns for the taxation years ended October 31, 2010, October 31, 2011, October 31, 2012 and October 31, 2013, the Minister relied on the facts set out in the previous paragraphs, together with the following facts:
<P3>i. the Appellant reported as income all Rebates paid by cheques issued to the Appellant;</P3>
<P3>ii. a material portion of the Rebates were selected to be paid by methods other than a cheque;</P3>
<P3>iii. the Rebates not paid by cheque were not reported as income by the Appellant;</P3>
<P3>iv. the Appropriated Rebates were used for the Shareholders' personal use;</P3>
<P3>v. there is no relationship between the Shareholders and the Pharmaceutical Manufacturers outside of the business relationship surrounding the Appellant;</P3>
<P3>vi. rebates in the pharmaceutical industry are very common and have consistently been treated as taxable income;</P3>
<P3>vii. the Shareholders began the pharmacy business in 2002 and were well aw are of the appropriate treatment of the Rebates;</P3>
<P3>viii. the Appellant and its Shareholders did not keep proper records of the Rebates received;</P3>
<P3>ix. the Shareholders did not include these benefits in the calculation of their personal income reported for tax; and</P3>
<P3>x. the amount of Rebates which the Appellant failed to report were substantial compared to the total amount of income reported by the Appellant in the taxation years ended October 31, 2010, October 31, 2011, October 31, 2012 and October 31, 2013.</P3></P2></P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>C.</N><TI>ISSUES TO BE DECIDED</TI>
<P><P1>14. The issues to be decided are whether:
<P2>a. the Appeal for the taxation year ended October 31, 2013 is validly instituted;</P2>
<P2>b. the Minister was entitled to reassess the Appellant's income tax returns for the taxation years ended October 31, 2010, October 31, 2011, October 31, 2012 and October 31, 2013 beyond the normal reassessment period; and</P2>
<P2>c. the Minister properly included unreported rebates and incentives of $6,078, $4,871, $8,744 and $4,480 in the taxation years ended October 31, 2010, October 31, 2011, October 31, 2012 and October 31, 2013, respectively.</P2></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>D.</N><TI>STATUTORY PROVISIONS, GROUNDS RELIED ON AND RELIEF SOUGHT</TI>
<P><P1>15. The Attorney General relies on section 3, subsections 9 (1), 12(1), 56(2), 152(4), 152(9) and paragraph 12(1)(x), of the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM>, R.S.C. 1985, c.1 (5th Supp.) as amended (&ldquo;<EM>Act</EM>&rdquo;).</P1>
<P1>16. The appeal for the taxation year ended October 31, 2013 ought to be quashed on the basis that the Minister has reassessed $nil tax, interest and penalties. Therefore, no rights of appeal in respect thereof.</P1>
<P1>17. The Attorney General submits that as the Appellant failed to report all of the Rebates it earned in the course of doing business with the Pharmaceutical Manufacturers, the Minister has properly reassessed the Appellant to include the unreported Rebates in its income pursuant to sections 3, 9 and 12 of the <EM>Act</EM>.</P1>
<P1>18. In the alternative, to the extent any of the Rebates were paid directly to the Shareholders, they are benefits conferred on the Shareholders at the Appellant's direction and must be included in the Appellant's income pursuant to subsection 56(2) of the <EM>Act</EM>.</P1>
<P1>19. Subsection 152(4) of the <EM>Act</EM> authorizes reassessment at any time where a taxpayer has made any misrepresentation attributable to neglect, carelessness or wilful default. The Appellant made such misrepresentation, therefore the Minister was not out of time to reassess its taxation years ended October 31, 2010, October 31, 2011, October 31, 2012 and October 31, 2013.</P1>
<P1>20. The Attorney General requests that the appeal be dismissed.</P1></P>
<P>All of which is respectfully submitted.</P>
